Sass Guidelines is an opinionated styleguide for writing sane, maintainable and
scalable Sass. It gathers years of experience working with large Sass codebases
into a single, long‑form document that teams can adopt as a shared reference.

{% info %}
**Disclaimer:** Sass Guidelines is no longer actively maintained. It remains
largely valid and usable, but does not account for latest developments in the
Sass ecosystem.
{% endinfo %}

## What it covers

- **Architecture and file structure**: how to split a codebase into meaningful
  layers and partials so that it scales beyond a single person.
- **Naming and conventions**: guidance for variables, mixins, functions,
  placeholders, and more so that code remains readable months or years later.
- **Patterns and anti‑patterns**: concrete examples of what tends to work well
  in real projects, and what almost always comes back to bite you.
- **Code samples**: plenty of snippets that can be copied, adapted and extended
  for your own projects.

The goal is not to define The One True Way™ of writing Sass, but to provide a
consistent, thoughtful baseline that people can push against, adapt and evolve.

## Reach and impact

Since its launch, Sass Guidelines has been read, translated and referenced by
teams all over the world. It has inspired internal coding standards, helped new
Sass users ramp up more confidently, and influenced how many people think about
CSS architecture in general.

The project lives at [sass-guidelin.es](https://sass-guidelin.es) and is fully
open‑source on GitHub, where people regularly discuss improvements, translations
and clarifications.

